00:16:56.190 --> 00:16:58.940
devices in case they're lost or stolen.

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:03.880
and you can prevent sensitive data
from falling into the wrong hands.

00:17:04.900 --> 00:17:10.290
So the way we do that with the iPhone
and iPhone 2.0 software is using

00:17:10.290 --> 00:17:12.900
something called configuration profiles.

00:17:13.050 --> 00:17:17.530
So here I'll take a sidebar and
describe more in detail what

00:17:17.530 --> 00:17:20.060
a configuration profile is.

00:17:20.200 --> 00:17:24.200
So a configuration profile is simply
a file full of device settings.

00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:28.500
So the simple XML plist files
that contain settings for

00:17:28.630 --> 00:17:33.700
things like email accounts,
security settings, networking setup,

00:17:33.790 --> 00:17:38.580
pretty much anything you could set up
directly on the iPhone for an end user.

00:17:38.910 --> 00:17:42.890
But the real power in configuration
profiles is that you can also set up

00:17:43.310 --> 00:17:47.530
things that you wouldn't want your end
users to configure by hand or things that

00:17:47.530 --> 00:17:50.100
there's no UI on the iPhone to configure.

00:17:52.150 --> 00:17:56.250
and configuration profiles are
installable by either email or

00:17:56.250 --> 00:17:59.340
Safari directly on the iPhone.

00:17:59.490 --> 00:18:02.420
What this means is that you don't
ever have to connect an iPhone in

00:18:02.420 --> 00:18:06.540
order to install these files and
configure it-- configure that iPhone.

00:18:06.650 --> 00:18:11.460
You could create a configuration profile,
post it on a secure web server or

00:18:11.460 --> 00:18:15.940
send it out to your users as email,
and they can install it on their iPhones

00:18:15.960 --> 00:18:18.940
without ever tethering the device.

00:18:20.090 --> 00:18:22.500
and of course,
iPhone Configuration Utility allows

00:18:22.500 --> 00:18:26.590
you to create configuration profiles.

00:18:26.780 --> 00:18:30.420
So, anything that a configuration
profile can set up on the iPhone,

00:18:30.420 --> 00:18:33.880
iPhone Configuration
Utility lets you configure.

00:18:33.880 --> 00:18:36.810
Things like passcode policies which,
you know,

00:18:36.960 --> 00:18:41.450
so you can actually require that your
users have a passcode on their iPhones,

00:18:41.570 --> 00:18:45.060
even setting the strength of
the passcode that they use,

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:47.940
or the maximum age in days.

00:18:47.940 --> 00:18:51.720
We can set up application restrictions
so that you can prevent your

00:18:51.720 --> 00:18:56.360
users from watching too much
YouTube or surfing on the net,

00:18:56.460 --> 00:18:58.080
surfing the web.

00:18:58.080 --> 00:19:00.910
You can,
and in exchange for accepting these

00:19:00.910 --> 00:19:05.100
security policies on your behalf,
the end users can get access

00:19:05.100 --> 00:19:09.240
to things you've set up such
as pre-canned email settings,

00:19:09.240 --> 00:19:12.960
or you can embed certificates in
these configuration profiles which

00:19:13.450 --> 00:19:18.840
you can use to simplify setting
up VPN access or Wi-Fi access.

00:19:18.840 --> 00:19:22.570
You can even set up
Exchange ActiveSync accounts.

00:19:23.940 --> 00:19:27.420
And again,
a lot of this would be pretty scary if it

