00:25:06.050 --> 00:25:09.610
So let's start with design.

00:25:10.100 --> 00:25:15.680
So what should you consider
putting on the iPhone?

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:19.220
It seems kind of simple,
but the answer can be elusive.

00:25:19.360 --> 00:25:22.560
As Bud mentioned,
everybody is going mobile.

00:25:22.710 --> 00:25:25.010
And like I said, it's simple.

00:25:25.110 --> 00:25:28.990
You need to build mobile applications
to address the needs of mobile users.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:32.990
And that means the people in your
organization who are mobile all the time,

00:25:32.990 --> 00:25:37.640
like people that are out in the field
doing sales or virtually anybody on a

00:25:37.640 --> 00:25:44.000
university campus or anybody in your
organization when they're out on the go.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:49.550
So you need to build applications
that help users with quick,

00:25:49.550 --> 00:25:50.880
quick tasks.

00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:55.090
Some examples are looking up something,
getting like a dictionary

00:25:55.090 --> 00:25:59.000
reference or following the
status of something in progress.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:04.000
Getting any kind of updates on what's
going on elsewhere in the organization.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:07.330
Apps that help you make
more informed decisions,

00:26:07.330 --> 00:26:09.940
keep you notified of what's going on.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.910
Or applications that let you control
what's going on in your organization from

00:26:13.910 --> 00:26:16.000
wherever you happen to be in the world.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:19.000
These are the real
advantages of the iPhone.

00:26:19.010 --> 00:26:23.320
Just to sum up real quick,
the takeaway from this slide is if it

00:26:23.370 --> 00:26:27.140
could make a good dashboard widget,
it would be a great

00:26:27.140 --> 00:26:29.000
candidate for an iPhone app.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:30.630
application.

00:26:31.890 --> 00:26:33.780
So once you've figured out
what you want to build,

00:26:33.790 --> 00:26:36.050
you have this question, "Well,
how am I going to build

00:26:36.100 --> 00:26:40.040
it?" And on the iPhone,
you have two platform options--yes, two.

00:26:40.150 --> 00:26:43.840
So the first is the native SDK,
which we all know about.

00:26:43.950 --> 00:26:47.540
But the second is you could
build it as a web application.

00:26:47.780 --> 00:26:49.220
Some of you--I'm not sure.

00:26:49.320 --> 00:26:52.900
Maybe half the room is already, "Yeah,
I'm not going to bother with native.

00:26:52.900 --> 00:26:56.560
I'm going to do web." But maybe
half the room is asking,

00:26:56.560 --> 00:26:59.000
"Now that I have an SDK,
why do I have to keep building web

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:02.650
applications?" And the answer is
the same reason you would build a

00:27:02.650 --> 00:27:04.680
web application for the desktop.

00:27:04.750 --> 00:27:08.650
There's no installation to worry about,
instant deployment, instant update.

00:27:08.830 --> 00:27:12.340
These are the things that within Apple we
value because we really need all of

00:27:12.340 --> 00:27:17.040
our users to be on the same version
of our software at any given moment.

00:27:17.280 --> 00:27:21.490
So if you need help making this decision,
I just put up some of the

00:27:21.490 --> 00:27:23.380
platform features available.

00:27:23.380 --> 00:27:28.040
Like I said, if instant deployment,
instant updates,

00:27:28.040 --> 00:27:31.540
and cross-platform compatibility
are important to you,

00:27:31.540 --> 00:27:33.720
you can't beat a web app.

00:27:33.730 --> 00:27:36.170
If, however,
your application needs access

00:27:36.170 --> 00:27:39.560
to some of the new spiffy
APIs like location services,

00:27:39.620 --> 00:27:45.330
camera services, audio or 3D graphics,
or if it needs to be able to work

00:27:45.330 --> 00:27:48.630
without an internet connection,
you really need to build

00:27:48.630 --> 00:27:49.760
it as a native application.

00:27:49.770 --> 00:27:52.020
It's just not an option.

00:27:52.050 --> 00:27:54.530
But for everything else,
most of the features that you

00:27:54.530 --> 00:27:58.090
want for your applications are
available in both platforms.

00:27:58.140 --> 00:28:00.910
They both integrate with all
the other apps on the phone.

00:28:01.040 --> 00:28:04.310
You can build the same iPhone look
and feel into your applications

00:28:04.350 --> 00:28:09.640
using Interface Builder if it's
native or Dashcode if it's a web app.

00:28:09.690 --> 00:28:13.420
Both platforms support the ability
to have a custom application icon

00:28:13.420 --> 00:28:16.590
added to the user's home screen.

00:28:16.650 --> 00:28:20.750
They both now support
multi-touch gestures.

00:28:20.750 --> 00:28:26.390
And with hardware-accelerated
CSS animation on the iPhone for web apps,

00:28:26.470 --> 00:28:30.350
your web apps are just going to
start to look just like native apps.

00:28:31.210 --> 00:28:34.300
If you're not sure which
way you want to go,

00:28:34.360 --> 00:28:37.500
I suggest looking at it this way.

00:28:37.590 --> 00:28:41.460
If you think about how often you
plan on updating your application

00:28:41.850 --> 00:28:46.540
versus how often you think users are
going to be using your application.

00:28:46.660 --> 00:28:50.160
And if you plot your application
somewhere in this space,

00:28:50.290 --> 00:28:54.660
you'll see that the more often
that people use it and the

00:28:54.660 --> 00:28:57.910
less often that you update it,
it would probably be a good

00:28:57.910 --> 00:29:00.230
candidate for a native application.

00:29:00.360 --> 00:29:03.200
But if users aren't going
to use it very often,

00:29:03.260 --> 00:29:07.360
but you're going to update it a lot,
it would probably be worth it to

00:29:07.360 --> 00:29:09.300
develop it as a web application.

00:29:09.440 --> 00:29:12.700
Now, I have some examples just so
you get a better feel of how

00:29:12.700 --> 00:29:14.360
things fall in this graph.

00:29:14.420 --> 00:29:17.110
The stocks widget on the phone.

00:29:17.140 --> 00:29:18.450
I don't even think it has been updated.

00:29:18.530 --> 00:29:19.940
It doesn't need to be updated.

00:29:20.030 --> 00:29:21.090
What we've got works fine.

00:29:21.100 --> 00:29:24.210
The only thing that would ever
cause it to need an update would

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:26.440
be if our data source dropped out.

00:29:26.530 --> 00:29:28.220
We'd need to change where it points.

00:29:28.370 --> 00:29:31.060
But it's never needed updating,
and the people that use

00:29:31.060 --> 00:29:32.020
it use it all the time.

00:29:32.300 --> 00:29:34.780
It's a great application for native.

00:29:35.020 --> 00:29:38.000
A lot of IT applications,
specifically business

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:42.360
forms and business reports,
need to change with your organization.

00:29:42.380 --> 00:29:46.390
So if you start selling a new product,
if your governance laws change,

00:29:46.490 --> 00:29:49.900
anything like that,
you need to update that application.

00:29:50.050 --> 00:29:52.510
And in some cases,
that means that every time

00:29:52.510 --> 00:29:55.600
somebody uses the app,
they need to get a new version.

00:29:55.730 --> 00:29:59.180
And that means it's better as a web app.

00:29:59.450 --> 00:30:04.680
The trick to this is noticing that
this slide is not evenly distributed.

00:30:04.780 --> 00:30:07.900
There's this hot spot where
native activity is really,

00:30:07.900 --> 00:30:09.940
really effective.

00:30:09.970 --> 00:30:13.120
And that's because even the
most popular application,

00:30:13.120 --> 00:30:16.050
the one that gets used
by users all the time,

00:30:16.300 --> 00:30:20.550
if you change it too often,
eventually it's not worth making users

00:30:20.610 --> 00:30:22.860
update a new version all the time.

00:30:22.900 --> 00:30:25.260
So a web app is a better choice.

00:30:25.310 --> 00:30:28.390
And on the other side,
even if you plan on never,

00:30:28.390 --> 00:30:32.990
ever changing your application,
if nobody's interested in using it,

00:30:32.990 --> 00:30:35.210
it's probably better as a web app.

00:30:35.370 --> 00:30:38.740
They can visit it when they need it.

00:30:38.740 --> 00:30:40.810
So,

00:30:42.190 --> 00:30:47.460
Like I said, and as Bud said,
in Apple we focus on web

00:30:47.460 --> 00:30:52.170
applications for the enterprise,
largely because it is critical

00:30:52.170 --> 00:30:55.140
that everybody be on the same
version and we don't want to make

00:30:55.140 --> 00:30:58.250
people have to go through any
setup or installation beforehand.

00:30:58.350 --> 00:31:01.180
So most of my talk from now on is
actually going to be focused on web apps.

00:31:01.300 --> 00:31:05.640
But before I leave native,
I want to talk about what makes

00:31:05.760 --> 00:31:07.590
a great iPhone application.

00:31:07.690 --> 00:31:11.250
Great iPhone applications are
the ones that help the user

00:31:11.250 --> 00:31:13.250
with getting something done.

00:31:13.490 --> 00:31:16.220
Getting something done
quickly without distraction,

00:31:16.330 --> 00:31:19.470
without taking up too much
of their time so that they

00:31:19.470 --> 00:31:21.860
can move on with their lives.

00:31:21.990 --> 00:31:24.410
Great applications are focused.

00:31:24.650 --> 00:31:28.280
They're not trying to solve every
problem that a computer could do.

00:31:28.450 --> 00:31:33.150
They're just trying to help you with
a specific task while you're mobile.

00:31:33.250 --> 00:31:34.850
They're fast.

00:31:34.940 --> 00:31:36.100
They need to load
quickly and run quickly.

00:31:36.100 --> 00:31:37.600
They need to load
quickly and run quickly.

00:31:37.600 --> 00:31:41.070
And they need to be ready to be
interrupted by a phone call or

00:31:41.180 --> 00:31:45.840
because the user really needs to turn
off their phone in class or whatever.

00:31:45.930 --> 00:31:50.000
And then they need to be
able to resume immediately.

00:31:51.030 --> 00:31:53.800
They are formatted not
only for the screen,

00:31:53.800 --> 00:31:56.180
which we all know is
not a desktop screen,

00:31:56.360 --> 00:31:59.150
but they're formatted for
use in a mobile setting.

00:31:59.450 --> 00:32:05.260
That means that your colors should
be readable at an arm's length in

00:32:05.260 --> 00:32:09.930
sunlight and your touch controls
should be big enough to touch and your

00:32:09.930 --> 00:32:13.060
text should be large enough to read.

00:32:13.200 --> 00:32:17.030
Great iPhone apps adopt the
UI conventions set forth by the

00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:21.260
iPhone to provide a familiar
experience to users so they don't

00:32:21.260 --> 00:32:23.730
take any time to learn how to use.

00:32:24.670 --> 00:32:29.200
And finally,
great iPhone applications integrate

00:32:29.280 --> 00:32:31.400
with other iPhone applications.

00:32:31.600 --> 00:32:36.270
You should provide links to dial phone
numbers if you have them or write new

00:32:36.270 --> 00:32:39.030
emails if you have them or get maps.

00:32:39.140 --> 00:32:42.390
These things users will
greatly appreciate.

00:32:43.660 --> 00:32:46.040
I have some great examples
from applications.

00:32:46.040 --> 00:32:48.880
One, the first I'm going to
start is a consumer example.

00:32:48.890 --> 00:32:51.100
Everybody could take out your iPhone.

00:32:51.100 --> 00:32:52.000
Please don't do it now.

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:53.910
You could all see this.

00:32:54.180 --> 00:32:55.990
It's fandango.com.

00:32:56.120 --> 00:33:00.310
If you're not familiar,
because I think they only work in the

00:33:00.340 --> 00:33:06.540
U.S., fandango is a website that offers
movie tickets and show times for users.

00:33:06.710 --> 00:33:11.390
Being a standards-compliant website,
it works wonderfully on the phone.

00:33:11.400 --> 00:33:12.400
It works beautifully.

00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:13.280
You can go there.

00:33:13.280 --> 00:33:16.900
You can do everything that
you could do normally.

00:33:16.970 --> 00:33:22.520
But fandango decided to build a
version of their site for the iPhone,

00:33:22.520 --> 00:33:23.970
and this is it.

00:33:24.120 --> 00:33:31.280
And why this is great is it's literally
a hundred times lighter weight.

00:33:31.310 --> 00:33:34.080
The size of the website
that has to be downloaded,

00:33:34.110 --> 00:33:36.420
the size that has to be hosted,
the size that has to be transferred

00:33:36.460 --> 00:33:39.860
and then loaded onto the phone
is literally a hundred times

00:33:39.860 --> 00:33:43.220
smaller than the original Fandango.

00:33:43.230 --> 00:33:48.360
It loads a hundred fewer
files from your web server.

00:33:48.370 --> 00:33:53.120
And all this adds up to seven
times faster loading on Wi-Fi.

00:33:53.490 --> 00:33:54.800
Well, probably seven times on anything.

00:33:55.040 --> 00:33:58.780
But it takes five
seconds to load on Wi-Fi.

00:34:01.040 --> 00:34:03.600
So this is an application that's focused.

00:34:03.600 --> 00:34:06.260
They didn't deliver everything
that Fandango's website has.

00:34:06.320 --> 00:34:09.860
There aren't photos or trailers,
but they have what you

00:34:09.860 --> 00:34:11.110
need when you're on the go.

00:34:11.120 --> 00:34:15.760
They have movie show times and they
have the ability to buy tickets.

00:34:15.760 --> 00:34:19.000
It's very fast, as I said,
loads in five seconds on Wi-Fi.

00:34:19.060 --> 00:34:22.510
It's formatted,
uses the same UI that people are

00:34:22.510 --> 00:34:27.600
familiar with on the iPhone using
the table view style navigation.

00:34:27.600 --> 00:34:29.700
And it's integrated.

00:34:29.700 --> 00:34:31.940
If you find a theater
and buy tickets there,

00:34:31.940 --> 00:34:35.040
then you can call to get directions
or you could just go to the

00:34:35.080 --> 00:34:37.280
Maps application and get directions.

