00:34:42.040 --> 00:34:45.540
we think a great example is a directory.

00:34:45.540 --> 00:34:50.040
My group built the Apple Directory app
that Scott Forstall

00:34:50.040 --> 00:34:53.690
demoed last year at WWDC,
which some of you may like

00:34:54.400 --> 00:34:56.610
because it shows that you can
actually develop web apps,

00:34:56.740 --> 00:35:01.040
but some of you may hate
because it was secretly telling

00:35:01.040 --> 00:35:03.450
you we don't have an SDK yet.

00:35:03.520 --> 00:35:05.040
But now we do.

00:35:05.300 --> 00:35:07.660
So we thought this was a good example.

00:35:07.760 --> 00:35:12.060
We took the very same Apple Directory web
application that we provide

00:35:12.060 --> 00:35:15.720
to our employees to look up
anybody else in the company,

00:35:15.720 --> 00:35:18.130
and we built it for the iPhone.

00:35:18.290 --> 00:35:19.780
And it's fast.

00:35:19.780 --> 00:35:23.960
Most calls come back
within three seconds.

00:35:24.060 --> 00:35:24.870
It's formatted.

00:35:25.050 --> 00:35:27.880
It fits perfectly on the screen.

00:35:27.880 --> 00:35:30.120
You don't need to zoom or pan.

00:35:30.350 --> 00:35:33.460
It offers the exact same
UI that's in your contact list.

00:35:33.460 --> 00:35:34.820
It's an integrated application.

00:35:34.820 --> 00:35:35.990
It's based on a contact book.

00:35:35.990 --> 00:35:37.770
So if users have already
dealt with contacts,

00:35:37.770 --> 00:35:39.760
they already know how
to use this application.

00:35:39.760 --> 00:35:40.230
And it's integrated.

00:35:40.260 --> 00:35:42.890
You can touch a phone
number to call a person.

00:35:42.900 --> 00:35:46.630
You can email a person directly
by touching their email address.

00:35:46.740 --> 00:35:50.770
Or you can touch their office
location to find out where they are.

00:35:53.570 --> 00:35:58.580
Now, phone books and movie
times are really fun,

00:35:58.690 --> 00:36:01.790
but IT data is a lot more
complicated than that,

00:36:01.790 --> 00:36:02.240
right?

00:36:02.240 --> 00:36:03.380
So you're saying, "Well, that's great.

00:36:03.390 --> 00:36:06.950
You guys made wonderful applications
that do this cute little toy stuff,

00:36:07.110 --> 00:36:08.310
but what about my data?

00:36:08.380 --> 00:36:09.340
My data is ugly.

00:36:09.390 --> 00:36:13.090
So how are you going to help
me?" So I wanted to show

00:36:13.090 --> 00:36:15.390
you a real business example.

00:36:15.400 --> 00:36:20.470
What we did was we were asked earlier
this year to port a sales report for

00:36:20.530 --> 00:36:23.400
the company from a web to the iPhone.

00:36:23.400 --> 00:36:29.800
And we did it using the same data,
the same database as the original report,

00:36:29.800 --> 00:36:32.990
so there's no conflict in numbers.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:38.170
We focused it, though, for real-time use,
and we format it to be

00:36:38.170 --> 00:36:40.200
used on the mobile device.

00:36:40.200 --> 00:36:41.690
And I'd like to show you how we did it.

00:36:41.700 --> 00:36:45.850
So this is an example of
the original sales report.

00:36:45.950 --> 00:36:49.560
It's not the real thing,
but it's an example.

00:36:49.630 --> 00:36:56.500
It shows actual and forecast sales
figures so far for a store so far today,

00:36:56.500 --> 00:37:01.240
this week and this quarter,
across the revenues that we

00:37:01.300 --> 00:37:05.100
make and then the rates of sale,
the products that we sell,

00:37:05.100 --> 00:37:06.600
and the services that we sell.

00:37:06.610 --> 00:37:11.600
And we use this to judge how we're doing.

00:37:11.600 --> 00:37:14.400
So we went back to our
previous business model,

00:37:14.400 --> 00:37:19.500
which was a web application, and we said,
"Okay, it has to make it onto the phone.

00:37:19.500 --> 00:37:21.500
We could just put it on the phone,
but that's not readable at all."

00:37:21.500 --> 00:37:24.340
So we went back and we said,
"Okay, we're going to have to put a

00:37:24.340 --> 00:37:26.960
little bit more effort into
it than that." So we said,

00:37:27.060 --> 00:37:30.370
"Well, what do people need when they're
checking -- if they're going to check

00:37:30.370 --> 00:37:33.430
this sales report on their phone,
what do they care about when they're

00:37:33.430 --> 00:37:37.330
not at their desk?" And we realized
that they don't care about how we're

00:37:37.330 --> 00:37:39.240
doing this week or this quarter.

00:37:39.240 --> 00:37:41.500
They care about how we're doing now.

00:37:41.500 --> 00:37:41.500
So we dropped that data.

00:37:41.660 --> 00:37:44.500
And they don't care about how
individual products are selling.

00:37:44.630 --> 00:37:46.500
They care about what kinds
of products are selling.

00:37:46.500 --> 00:37:48.490
So we summarized that data.

00:37:48.490 --> 00:37:50.500
And that gave us a much
more manageable data set.

00:37:50.500 --> 00:37:54.500
So again, we said, "Okay,
a good day's work, right?

00:37:54.500 --> 00:37:55.500
We solved that problem.

00:37:55.500 --> 00:38:00.500
Works okay on the phone."
But that didn't please everybody.

00:38:00.500 --> 00:38:03.830
So we said, "Okay,
we need to format this for mobile

00:38:03.870 --> 00:38:07.500
use." And what we did was we
completely reimagined the data.

00:38:07.500 --> 00:38:09.860
It's the same data,
but we've completely changed

00:38:09.860 --> 00:38:11.400
the visual representation.

00:38:11.400 --> 00:38:16.400
We've chosen to use icons instead
of category names to save space.

00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:21.270
And that made room for these bar graphs,
which let you look at comparable numbers

00:38:21.400 --> 00:38:23.300
immediately and know how you're doing.

00:38:23.300 --> 00:38:26.290
So in this case,
we're beating the pants off our forecast.

00:38:26.300 --> 00:38:30.850
So this is -- oh, yeah,
and we separated it into a revenue

00:38:30.860 --> 00:38:33.300
section and a unit section.

00:38:33.300 --> 00:38:37.120
So this gives users a less cluttered
view and some visual cues to

00:38:37.130 --> 00:38:41.300
help them read the data without
actually having to read the data.

00:38:41.410 --> 00:38:44.650
Which means that they can see
how we're doing and then put

00:38:44.650 --> 00:38:46.530
it back in their pocket and go.

00:38:46.820 --> 00:38:50.070
This is the unit side where we
show some of our product families

00:38:50.080 --> 00:38:54.180
how they're selling and some of
the services how we're doing.

00:38:54.980 --> 00:38:57.230
So we thought this was a pretty
good example of an iPhone app.

00:38:57.310 --> 00:39:01.470
It's focused just on today's data,
and we've summarized the data

00:39:01.470 --> 00:39:04.400
to be what the user cares
about when they're on the go.

00:39:04.460 --> 00:39:05.080
It's fast.

00:39:05.160 --> 00:39:10.030
The whole app loads within five seconds,
and real-time updates

00:39:10.030 --> 00:39:12.240
come within two seconds.

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:14.000
and it's formatted.

00:39:14.100 --> 00:39:15.570
It's built pixel for pixel.

00:39:15.660 --> 00:39:16.750
This is the screen size.

00:39:16.990 --> 00:39:18.870
You don't have to zoom in or pan.

00:39:18.990 --> 00:39:20.940
Minimal scrolling.

00:39:20.950 --> 00:39:22.980
It's pretty nice.

00:39:23.030 --> 00:39:27.010
Now I'm going to talk a little bit
about developing these applications.

00:39:28.120 --> 00:39:30.890
And I'm going to do it from
the perspective I know best,

00:39:30.890 --> 00:39:34.330
which is,
what do we do inside the company?

00:39:34.500 --> 00:40:56.600
[Transcript missing]

00:40:56.880 --> 00:41:00.180
and David What we're really
excited about now are the new

00:41:00.360 --> 00:41:05.180
web development technologies
that are available in iPhone 2.0.

00:41:05.180 --> 00:41:08.920
You can now do multi-touch
gesture events in the DOM,

00:41:09.020 --> 00:41:10.140
in JavaScript.

00:41:10.140 --> 00:41:14.370
You can respond just like on click,
you can respond to on touch or on pinch,

00:41:14.370 --> 00:41:15.100
I think.

00:41:15.100 --> 00:41:17.700
I don't know if they have a pinch.

00:41:17.700 --> 00:41:21.160
But you can react to multi-touch events.

00:41:21.160 --> 00:41:23.950
And then with hardware
accelerated CSS animation,

00:41:23.950 --> 00:41:26.720
people will forget that
they're using a web app.

00:41:26.720 --> 00:41:29.460
They'll think they're
using a native application.

00:41:29.460 --> 00:41:35.110
And the new feature in WebKit is
client-side persistence.

00:41:35.150 --> 00:41:38.760
So if you need to store any files
or anything from a web application,

00:41:38.760 --> 00:41:42.170
you can do it on the phone.

00:41:43.470 --> 00:41:45.100
So next I'd like to talk
about the dev tools.

00:41:45.100 --> 00:41:49.710
Now, if you saw the keynote yesterday,
Scott mentioned we've got a great

00:41:49.720 --> 00:41:52.660
set of developer tools for you
to build native applications,

00:41:52.660 --> 00:41:54.240
but he forgot one of my favorites.

00:41:54.240 --> 00:41:56.140
He forgot Dashcode.

00:41:56.150 --> 00:42:00.020
Dashcode is an amazing IDE for
building web applications,

00:42:00.130 --> 00:42:01.940
and it's even better now.

00:42:01.940 --> 00:42:05.560
I don't know if you've
taken a look at it recently.

00:42:05.590 --> 00:42:08.830
And the iPhone simulator isn't just
for simulating your native apps.

00:42:08.940 --> 00:42:13.500
It has the mobile Safari in it,
and you can test your web applications

00:42:13.500 --> 00:42:17.780
in the iPhone simulator as if you were
actually testing them on the phone.

00:42:18.030 --> 00:42:20.640
So Dashcode is a dual-mode editor.

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:23.620
You can put your applications
together by writing them in code,

00:42:23.660 --> 00:42:28.360
or you can just drag and drop
components to edit--assemble

00:42:28.360 --> 00:42:29.800
your application graphically.

00:42:29.850 --> 00:42:32.560
It's very much like
Interface Builder and Xcode.

00:42:32.560 --> 00:42:36.080
It has many iPhone templates
to get you started building an

00:42:36.080 --> 00:42:39.360
iPhone application very quickly.

00:42:39.390 --> 00:42:41.400
And it has a rich component library.

00:42:41.400 --> 00:42:42.910
I can't say enough
nice things about this.

00:42:42.980 --> 00:42:47.390
The Dashcode team has done some amazing
work building reusable components that

00:42:47.390 --> 00:42:50.480
you can put into your application so
that you don't have to worry about

00:42:50.480 --> 00:42:53.090
how lists work or how buttons work.

00:42:53.170 --> 00:42:57.170
And they've got great sliding animations,
even flip animations.

00:42:57.240 --> 00:43:02.180
You can make it look like you spent
twice as much time on your application.

00:43:02.830 --> 00:43:05.300
and David Schmuck,
and I'm going to give you a little

00:43:05.300 --> 00:43:05.700
bit of background on what DashCode is.

00:43:05.700 --> 00:43:07.790
DashCode has a great
debugging environment for

00:43:07.790 --> 00:43:11.700
JavaScript and web applications,
which I know if you've done

00:43:11.700 --> 00:43:13.780
any web app development,
you should be very pleased to

00:43:13.780 --> 00:43:17.700
know that you can actually debug
JavaScript applications more

00:43:17.700 --> 00:43:17.700
like native applications now.

00:43:17.700 --> 00:43:20.910
And if you want to,
DashCode even lets you do one-click

00:43:20.940 --> 00:43:22.640
deployment to a web server.

00:43:22.990 --> 00:43:26.010
All you have to do is
just work in DashCode,

00:43:26.130 --> 00:43:31.430
test in the simulator,
and then hit share, and then it's out.

00:43:31.430 --> 00:43:31.430
Everybody knows about it.

00:43:32.590 --> 00:43:35.400
The iPhone simulator, like I said,
has the exact same version of

00:43:35.400 --> 00:43:36.830
Safari that's on the phone.

00:43:36.910 --> 00:43:41.250
So you can see how the viewport
and rotation events and multitouch

00:43:41.250 --> 00:43:45.190
gestures affect the application
when it's actually deployed.

00:43:45.270 --> 00:43:48.520
You can even see the real on-screen
keyboards that users see when

00:43:48.630 --> 00:43:53.560
they're using their iPhones and
check out the home screen icon,

00:43:53.560 --> 00:43:56.720
which you may build for your web
application so users can save

00:43:56.720 --> 00:43:59.180
it right on their home screen.

00:44:01.100 --> 00:44:05.600
So, over about a year of--yeah,
a little over a year--of iPhone

00:44:05.690 --> 00:44:09.100
development for the enterprise,
we've picked up a few tricks.

00:44:09.100 --> 00:44:12.960
I don't know if you know these yet,
but number one, if you can help it,

00:44:13.140 --> 00:44:14.630
build a one-page application.

00:44:14.680 --> 00:44:17.840
One HTML page and then everything
happens asynchronously,

00:44:17.840 --> 00:44:18.440
dynamic.

00:44:18.570 --> 00:44:22.380
This will save you a lot of bandwidth,
save you a lot of time.

00:44:22.380 --> 00:44:25.700
It's a lot easier to carry data
from screen to screen when you're

00:44:25.700 --> 00:44:29.180
not actually having to take it
from one screen to another screen.

00:44:29.410 --> 00:44:31.860
And users get a better experience
because they don't have to

00:44:31.900 --> 00:44:32.900
load more than one page.

00:44:33.110 --> 00:44:37.000
Once the app is there,
they don't have to wait ever again.

00:44:37.210 --> 00:44:40.460
and David Seifert are all great people.

00:44:40.460 --> 00:44:41.460
Separate your static content
like CSS and JavaScript.

00:44:41.550 --> 00:44:44.440
If it's not going to change, pull it out.

00:44:44.440 --> 00:44:47.850
Make them separate files and then
deliver them to your users with

00:44:47.850 --> 00:44:51.240
HTTP compression so you can get
them to the users much faster.

00:44:51.240 --> 00:44:52.600
The iPhone will support it.

00:44:52.600 --> 00:44:54.020
It will unfold the code.

00:44:54.020 --> 00:44:58.520
It will load much faster, much quicker.

00:44:58.520 --> 00:45:03.660
New in WebKit every day practically
are some great technologies

00:45:03.740 --> 00:45:06.050
to help you render with CSS.

00:45:06.060 --> 00:45:09.360
That means that you can
use things like borders,

00:45:09.460 --> 00:45:13.440
gradients, transparency and shadows
-- these are just a few,

00:45:13.440 --> 00:45:17.240
there's masks and reflections
too -- to actually build your

00:45:17.240 --> 00:45:22.120
UI without loading a single image,
which is, I don't have to tell you,

00:45:22.120 --> 00:45:24.040
much more lightweight.

00:45:24.040 --> 00:45:26.740
And then for the images that
you just can't get rid of,

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:29.860
the whiz-bang graphics that
you just can't replace,

00:45:30.100 --> 00:45:34.100
you really need to use the
CSS sprite technique where you take,

00:45:34.240 --> 00:45:35.360
if you're not familiar,
you take a little bit of a little bit of

00:45:35.360 --> 00:45:38.170
a little bit of a little So you take all
of your different graphics and you stitch

00:45:38.170 --> 00:45:42.330
them together into a single image file
and then you use CSS to determine which

00:45:42.370 --> 00:45:47.300
part of that image shows on the screen
in any given position or any given time.

00:45:47.300 --> 00:45:50.500
That means you load one
image file instead of how

00:45:50.670 --> 00:45:53.220
many images are in your app,
50?

00:45:53.220 --> 00:45:54.600
I don't know.

00:45:54.690 --> 00:45:57.600
And it makes your app load much
faster and then it's precached.

00:45:57.600 --> 00:46:00.450
You know,
if you loaded the one image that's

00:46:00.450 --> 00:46:05.360
all the images in the application you
don't have to load it again later.

00:46:05.360 --> 00:46:08.460
demo of how that, yeah, sorry.

00:46:09.970 --> 00:46:14.140
So finally, I'd like to talk very
briefly about deployment.

00:46:14.210 --> 00:46:18.900
As Steve mentioned yesterday,
enterprise IT groups can deploy

00:46:19.120 --> 00:46:26.870
native applications for their
users on an internal site.

00:46:26.990 --> 00:46:30.510
Users visit the site,
they can open--they can

00:46:30.670 --> 00:46:35.130
download the--your in-house
applications to their computer,

00:46:35.240 --> 00:46:39.020
open them in iTunes and then
sideload them through it

00:46:39.070 --> 00:46:40.880
to their tethered iPhones.

00:46:40.940 --> 00:46:42.770
And that's great.

00:46:42.920 --> 00:46:46.970
So we know how you can deploy
native applications without having

00:46:46.970 --> 00:46:49.330
to be part of the public app store.

00:46:49.400 --> 00:46:54.220
You could be part of the public app
store and secure your application with

00:46:54.220 --> 00:46:56.930
employee passwords if you wanted to.

00:46:57.940 --> 00:47:02.230
But as I said, we do web app deployment,
and we found that after we built

00:47:02.380 --> 00:47:06.010
our first web app for the iPhone,
we had to find a place to host it,

00:47:06.010 --> 00:47:10.120
which was actually surprisingly
difficult for a computer company.

00:47:10.250 --> 00:47:13.580
We have to find a machine,
and then we have to get into the network,

00:47:13.580 --> 00:47:16.600
and then we have to get a domain for it,
and we have to go through

00:47:16.600 --> 00:47:18.760
all this red tape,
and then we have to expose

00:47:18.760 --> 00:47:21.080
it to the outside world,
because we wanted to make

00:47:21.080 --> 00:47:24.080
it convenient for users,
so we had to poke a hole in the firewall,

00:47:24.240 --> 00:47:28.000
and then we had to secure that hole so
only Apple employees could get into it.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:30.080
More bureaucracy.

00:47:30.160 --> 00:47:32.940
And then finally,
we had to tell everybody where we put it.

00:47:32.940 --> 00:47:35.390
We had to send out a company-wide email
that we've got this great new app,

00:47:35.390 --> 00:47:38.000
and now you can go there,
and here's a link to it.

00:47:38.040 --> 00:47:39.810
And then we had an app.

00:47:40.310 --> 00:47:45.340
Which was okay, but before we finished
building our second app,

00:47:45.340 --> 00:47:47.950
we kind of realized this
process won't scale.

00:47:48.160 --> 00:47:49.340
We can't do this every time.

00:47:49.340 --> 00:47:53.460
This is twice as much time as it
took to develop the application

00:47:53.460 --> 00:47:54.800
just to get it out to people.

00:47:54.840 --> 00:47:56.320
That's no good.

00:47:56.350 --> 00:48:01.990
So our solution was to build an
enterprise mobile application portal.

00:48:02.500 --> 00:48:08.300
We gave one URL for users to go to to
get all of the internal software that

00:48:08.300 --> 00:48:10.480
we were going to deploy on the iPhone.

00:48:10.550 --> 00:48:12.400
It means one entry point for security.

00:48:12.400 --> 00:48:15.390
Security is much happier now.

00:48:15.530 --> 00:48:17.700
And it's one host for
our iPhone applications.

00:48:17.700 --> 00:48:21.930
So now that we have one host ready to go,
we can deploy applications

00:48:21.930 --> 00:48:23.170
almost at will.

00:48:23.310 --> 00:48:24.200
and the rest of the team.

00:48:24.200 --> 00:48:26.840
And that means that users can bookmark
it right on their home screen.

00:48:26.840 --> 00:48:29.040
All their Apple apps are right here.

00:48:29.160 --> 00:48:31.780
They just touch it, it opens in Safari.

00:48:31.780 --> 00:48:34.150
If they're not authenticated,
we stop them.

00:48:34.230 --> 00:48:35.980
Then you have to explain who you are.

00:48:35.980 --> 00:48:38.120
We take a name and password.

00:48:38.120 --> 00:48:40.800
There are actually several
options for authenticating users,

00:48:40.800 --> 00:48:44.420
and Curtis will talk a lot
about that in just a minute.

00:48:44.420 --> 00:48:47.060
Once you've presented your credentials,
then we present you with the

00:48:47.060 --> 00:48:51.400
mobile portal with links to all the
applications that we have to date.

00:48:51.400 --> 00:48:54.300
And then they're one one
touch away from the user.

00:48:55.450 --> 00:49:00.540
So to recap, focus your applications on
solving particular problems.

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:01.980
You don't need to do everything.

00:49:01.980 --> 00:49:05.040
You just need to do something well.

00:49:05.080 --> 00:49:07.640
Load your applications
quick and run fast,

00:49:07.730 --> 00:49:09.760
even if you're on 3G iPhones.

00:49:09.830 --> 00:49:11.580
Quicker is better.

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:14.100
and format for mobile use.

00:49:14.350 --> 00:49:16.880
Remember, not just the screen,
the mobile context.

00:49:16.880 --> 00:49:20.060
Users are outside in the sunlight,
maybe they're driving in their car,

00:49:20.200 --> 00:49:23.980
god forbid, but whatever it may be.

00:49:23.980 --> 00:49:27.770
Use familiar UI concepts and
people won't have to learn.

00:49:27.890 --> 00:49:32.140
One of the things that we are
doing now is cutting training time

00:49:32.140 --> 00:49:36.790
out of all of our software by sort
of standardizing the experience.

00:49:36.800 --> 00:49:42.700
And you can integrate with the phone,
mail, other applications like Maps.

00:49:42.710 --> 00:49:46.060
Users really appreciate
those convenience touches.

00:49:46.120 --> 00:49:50.740
Definitely, definitely,
definitely go to Dash Code.

00:49:50.780 --> 00:49:56.440
Dash Code is gonna save you so much time,
it's not even funny.

00:49:56.840 --> 00:49:59.810
And the iPhone simulator,
it's not just for native applications,

00:49:59.890 --> 00:50:02.710
it'll help you test your web app too.

00:50:02.900 --> 00:50:05.860
If you have a
server-oriented architecture,

00:50:05.900 --> 00:50:08.910
your iPhone applications can
just hook into that if you

00:50:08.910 --> 00:50:10.660
just build Java serverlets,
like we did.

00:50:10.660 --> 00:50:14.600
If you don't have a
service-oriented architecture,

00:50:14.640 --> 00:50:16.600
this is the payoff.

00:50:16.600 --> 00:50:19.160
If you've been sort of holding out like,
well, I don't see why I should go through

00:50:19.160 --> 00:50:22.450
this extra trouble to build a
service-oriented architecture if

00:50:22.450 --> 00:50:24.300
I still have to do all this extra work.

00:50:24.350 --> 00:50:25.380
This is the payoff.

00:50:25.420 --> 00:50:28.030
This is where you get to reuse
stuff and then move for free.

00:50:28.100 --> 00:50:29.810
Cuts development time in half.

