00:51:21.600 --> 00:51:25.590
So you've deployed iPhones,
you've deployed applications.

00:51:26.030 --> 00:51:29.710
Hopefully you thought upfront
about all the security issues.

00:51:29.830 --> 00:51:33.590
How do you securely connect to
phones in your organizations?

00:51:33.600 --> 00:51:36.320
How do you make sure
the data is kept secure?

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:41.430
And luckily we have a ton of
technologies to help you do that,

00:51:41.440 --> 00:51:47.600
ranging from VPN technology
to SSL to things like 802.1X,

00:51:47.600 --> 00:51:53.540
things like remote wipe or
setting--configuring pin strength

00:51:53.600 --> 00:51:56.380
or pin policies for your users.

00:51:56.810 --> 00:52:01.510
So to talk about that,
we have Curtis Galloway who will

00:52:01.650 --> 00:52:04.520
come and fill us in on security.

00:52:04.650 --> 00:52:05.540
Curtis?

00:52:11.540 --> 00:52:12.460
Thanks, bud.

00:52:12.460 --> 00:52:14.500
So I'm Curtis Galloway.

00:52:14.500 --> 00:52:16.500
I'm in the iPhone Engineering Department.

00:52:16.500 --> 00:52:20.800
And I'm going to talk a little
bit about security on the iPhone.

00:52:20.800 --> 00:52:26.680
So secure access for deploying
the iPhone in your organization,

00:52:26.680 --> 00:52:29.930
you have your servers
with your data on it,

00:52:30.150 --> 00:52:33.780
and you have iPhones
in your organization.

00:52:33.800 --> 00:52:39.870
And you want to be able to make sure that
the data on your servers is not getting

00:52:39.870 --> 00:52:42.700
out of where you think it should be.

00:52:42.720 --> 00:52:46.140
You want to keep control of
that and keep control of your

00:52:46.410 --> 00:52:48.760
assets that are based on that.

00:52:48.760 --> 00:52:51.720
The most basic part of that is
securing your wireless network,

00:52:51.720 --> 00:52:54.600
because that's the primary
way that you're going to

00:52:54.740 --> 00:52:56.580
access data from the iPhone.

00:52:56.580 --> 00:53:02.280
And we've already had
on the existing iPhone,

00:53:02.280 --> 00:53:05.610
we have some amount of that,
but there's some new features about that.

00:53:05.610 --> 00:53:08.220
When you're outside of your -- Yeah.

00:53:09.220 --> 00:53:09.960
-- local enterprise,
you're going to access your

00:53:10.050 --> 00:53:13.980
corporate network through VPN,
so we have some improvements there.

00:53:14.110 --> 00:53:17.460
And certificates are another
way of increasing the security

00:53:17.460 --> 00:53:21.650
on the phone by improving the
identification of your users and of

00:53:21.650 --> 00:53:24.400
the resources that they're accessing.

00:53:24.430 --> 00:53:27.320
And also,
you're able to set security policies

00:53:27.850 --> 00:53:31.620
for iPhones that are owned by your
enterprise so that you can have

00:53:31.620 --> 00:53:35.970
increased control and confidence
over how they're being used.

00:53:36.390 --> 00:53:40.000
So first of all,
for Wi-Fi access security,

00:53:40.040 --> 00:53:44.430
we've previously supported WEP,
WPA Personal, WPA2 Personal.

00:53:44.540 --> 00:53:48.760
And in the new iPhone software release,
we've added enterprise-level

00:53:48.850 --> 00:53:50.340
support for authentication.

00:53:50.400 --> 00:53:54.280
So now we have WPA Enterprise,
WPA2 Enterprise,

00:53:54.280 --> 00:54:00.260
and 802.1X authentication with EAP TLS,
EAP TTLS, and EAP Fast,

00:54:00.260 --> 00:54:02.200
as well as PEEP and LEAP.

00:54:02.260 --> 00:54:05.580
And so that gives you a lot more
flexibility for authenticating

00:54:05.590 --> 00:54:08.200
users on your local Wi-Fi network.

00:54:08.270 --> 00:54:13.050
So now you can, within your enterprise,
have a secure wireless connection

00:54:13.120 --> 00:54:16.420
to access your corporate assets.

00:54:17.230 --> 00:54:21.660
On the VPN front,
we've previously had support for L2TP,

00:54:21.760 --> 00:54:27.580
IPSec and PPTP with name and password,
token-based authentication.

00:54:27.690 --> 00:54:29.790
And that's been okay,
but a lot of you have been asking for

00:54:29.790 --> 00:54:34.840
increased support for Cisco IPSec,
and so we have that now

00:54:35.210 --> 00:54:38.100
in our enterprise-level
VPN support on the iPhone.

00:54:38.110 --> 00:54:44.100
So you can use name and password,
secure ID tokens, crypto card tokens,

00:54:44.100 --> 00:54:48.100
and certificate-based authentication
with your Cisco network.

00:54:48.210 --> 00:54:53.360
And we think that is going to give you a
lot more flexibility with the equipment

00:54:53.360 --> 00:54:56.260
that you're able to use for VPN access.

00:54:59.430 --> 00:55:03.600
In the VPN configuration front,
you can use the iPhone configuration

00:55:03.600 --> 00:55:10.170
utility to configure your user's
VPN access so they don't have to

00:55:10.170 --> 00:55:13.600
go into the UI and select it and
configure all that stuff on their own.

00:55:13.600 --> 00:55:17.620
You can simply create a configuration
profile for them that has all of the

00:55:17.620 --> 00:55:22.690
settings for your company VPN that you
can deliver to them either on the web

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:29.520
or via e-mail or with tethered usage
of the iPhone configuration utility.

00:55:31.420 --> 00:55:34.690
For certificate usage,
we allow you now to install

00:55:34.690 --> 00:55:37.490
root trust certificates for
your organization so that if you

00:55:37.570 --> 00:55:42.640
have your own signing authority,
you can add your own root CA certificate

00:55:43.060 --> 00:55:47.170
so that users can trust all of the
certificates generated by that.

00:55:47.240 --> 00:55:48.410
That's very convenient.

00:55:48.490 --> 00:55:53.370
And we can also allow you to
pre-install server certificates so

00:55:53.440 --> 00:55:58.540
that they can trust your servers
implicitly without having any warnings.

00:55:58.570 --> 00:56:02.400
And identity certificates for
credentials for both VPN and Wi-Fi,

00:56:02.400 --> 00:56:07.610
you can pre-configure those and
deliver them in a configuration

00:56:07.610 --> 00:56:10.050
profile for the phone.

00:56:11.420 --> 00:56:16.120
For certificates,
we support PKCS #1 and the common file

00:56:16.120 --> 00:56:21.900
formats for that for root CA certificates
and server identity certificates,

00:56:21.910 --> 00:56:27.200
and also PKCS #12 for user
identity certificates,

00:56:27.200 --> 00:56:30.400
which include the encrypted
private key inside of them.

00:56:30.440 --> 00:56:35.770
And those are easily generated
by a lot of different forms.

00:56:35.810 --> 00:56:38.970
You can export them from keychain
access on a Mac if you already

00:56:38.970 --> 00:56:40.400
have Macs in your organization.

00:56:40.400 --> 00:56:46.360
Most certificate authorities can already
generate these files and export them.

00:56:46.360 --> 00:56:50.730
And the iPhone configuration utility
can also import them and include

00:56:50.730 --> 00:56:55.170
them in a device profile so that it's
all packaged up together for you.

00:56:55.950 --> 00:56:58.980
and you can import raw certificate
files through Mail and Safari.

00:56:59.060 --> 00:57:02.600
So if you just have the
certificate file by itself,

00:57:02.830 --> 00:57:06.600
you can add that as an attachment
and you're able to import that

00:57:06.600 --> 00:57:10.350
just as if it were a configuration
profile with one certificate in it.

00:57:10.510 --> 00:57:11.390
So that's very convenient.

00:57:11.390 --> 00:57:15.510
It doesn't require any additional
tools for generating those.

00:57:17.900 --> 00:57:21.400
As you can see,
the iPhone configuration utility

00:57:21.400 --> 00:57:23.290
gives you a tab to manage credentials.

00:57:23.360 --> 00:57:26.390
You can include multiple
certificates in a profile.

00:57:26.390 --> 00:57:31.200
So if you have an identity certificate,
a root CA and some server certificates,

00:57:31.220 --> 00:57:35.280
you can add those all together and
include them in one profile that you

00:57:35.350 --> 00:57:38.590
can easily install on a user's device.

00:57:38.980 --> 00:57:42.900
And if you want to deploy the
certificates by themselves,

00:57:42.950 --> 00:57:45.140
they just show up as
an attachment in email.

00:57:45.330 --> 00:57:48.070
So that's a very convenient
way to distribute them.

00:57:48.190 --> 00:57:52.880
And then it gets installed just as if it
were a profile and looks just like that.

00:57:52.880 --> 00:57:56.880
It can be managed on the
phone in a similar fashion.

00:57:58.600 --> 00:59:47.900
[Transcript missing]

00:59:48.330 --> 00:59:53.060
And we also have the ability to
do a remote wipe of the device.

00:59:53.060 --> 00:59:58.400
So if it's lost or stolen,
we have that out in the world somewhere,

00:59:58.400 --> 01:00:02.340
you can use Exchange Server to
actually send a wipe command and

01:00:02.340 --> 01:00:07.040
guarantee that that device is
going to have all its data erased.

01:00:07.090 --> 01:00:11.300
The actual flaming is a premium feature.

01:00:12.600 --> 01:00:17.340
So in summary, we have a number of new
features in the iPhone 2.0.

01:00:17.340 --> 01:00:24.300
We have secure Wi-Fi access with 802.11
Enterprise and 802.1X authentication.

01:00:24.350 --> 01:00:29.500
We have VPN access
improved with Cisco IPSec,

01:00:29.510 --> 01:00:34.000
which can be configured
through configuration profiles.

01:00:34.080 --> 01:00:38.540
And certificates for trust and identity,
you can include root CA certificate.

01:00:38.720 --> 01:00:42.170
You can include user
identity certificates.

01:00:42.270 --> 01:00:46.500
And we have the ability to set
security policies for your devices

01:00:47.130 --> 01:00:51.340
for application installation,
for device restrictions and for remote

01:00:51.340 --> 01:00:53.900
wipe to ensure the security of your data.

01:00:53.900 --> 01:00:58.890
That's it.

